From the explicit factor of 1=N multiplying the two-point function of the O/ field and the last term in the effective action (2.15) it is clear that the fluctuations of the composite O/ field enter the discussion at one higher order of 1=N than the original scalar OE field, whose fluctuations couple to the mean fields already at lowest order through the Tr ln G\Gamma 1 term in the effective action. The fact that O/ is an auxilliary field introduced into the discussion only for convenience and not a true propagating degree of freedom is reflected in the fact that there is no differential kinetic operator appearing in the expression for D\Gamma 1 (unlike in the definition of G\Gamma 1). The O/ field has no independent dynamics of its own, and its fluctuations are determined by those of the OE field. The last term in (2.16), namely

\Pi [O/] j \Gamma i2 G[O/]G[O/] (2:17) is the one loop vacuum polarization of the O/ field due to its interaction with the fluctuating OE field. It is included at the same order as the point vertex 1=* in the large N method because all loops of the OE field are exhanced by a factor of N (for the N identical OE fields) relative to what one would expect in an ordinary perturbative loop expansion. Finally we remark that

\Sigma (x; y) j iG(x; y)D(y; x) (2:18)

