1 0 C\Gamma dt : (3:20) A second simplification is possible in the form of the generating functional of (3.17), if we recognize that it is always possible to express the matrix elements of the density matrix as an exponential of a polynomial in the fields [5]:

h'1jaej'2 i = exp ^R + Z d3~x Ra(~x)'a(~x) + Z d3~xd3~y Rab(~x; ~y)'a(~x)'b(~y) + : : :* :

(3:21) Since any density matrix can be expressed in this form, there is no loss of generality involved in expressing ae as an exponential. If we add this exponent to that of the action in (3.17), and integrate over the two endpoints of the closed time path '1 and '2, then the only effect of the non-trivial density matrix ae is to introduce source terms into the path integral for ZC[J; ae] with support only at the endpoints. This means that the density matrix can only influence the boundary conditions on the path integral at t = 0, where the various coefficient functions Ra, Rab, etc. have the simple interpretations of initial conditions on the one-point (mean field), two-point (propagator), functions etc. It is clear that the equations of motion for t 6= 0 are not influenced by the presence of these terms at t = 0. In the special case that the initial density matrix describes a thermal state, aefi = expf\Gamma fiHg then the trace over aefi may be represented as an additional functional integration over fields along the purely imaginary contour from t = \Gamma ifi to t = 0 traversed before C\Gamma in Fig. 2. In this way the Feynman rules for real time thermal Green's functions are obtained [13]. Since we consider general nonequilibrium initial conditions here we have only the general expression for the initial ae above and no contour along the negative imaginary axis in Fig. 2.

To summarize, we may take over all the results of the previous section on the generating functionals, effective actions, and equations of motion of scalar \Phi 4 theory and QED, provided only that we

21

1. substitute the CTP path ordered Green's function(s) (3.18) for the ordinary

Feynman propagators in internal lines;

2. integrate over the full closed time contour, C, according to (3.20); and 3. satisfy the conditions at t = 0 corresponding to the initial density matrix ae.

